<div class="story-body">
  <p>Cybersecurity is not a First World/Third World, North vs South, issue, but a global one. 
    Every country has a vested interest in protecting information and keeping citizens safe. 
    But there is a difference in how each country handles it.</p>
  <p>Effective cybersecurity is absolutely critical in a world that is increasingly interconnected, as people rely on online services, digitally connected devices, and Internet of Things for work, communications, entertainment, education, and commerce. 
    An attack can disrupt company operations and a data breach can compromise the consumer's ability to shop online. 
    </p>
  <p>Countries have to balance a number of technical, legal, policy, and security decisions as part of their cybersecurity strategy. 
    The Global Cybersecurity Index (GCI) measures "the commitment of countries to cybersecurity," according to the International Telecommunication Union, a United Nations agency. 
    The index recognizes there are multiple dimensions to the issue, and that just doing one thing well isn't sufficient. 
    The idea of the GCI is to show that security is a journey, and each country has its own path to follow.</p>
</div>

